President Barack Obama has issued a proclamation declaring May 19-25, 2013, as World Trade Week. In the proclamation, President Obama emphasizes the importance of creating jobs in America by boosting manufacturing and expanding trade. He highlights the progress made under the National Export Initiative and the efforts to help businesses access new markets abroad. The President also calls for investments in commerce and infrastructure, such as modernizing roads, bridges, and ports, to facilitate faster and cheaper shipping of American goods and attract more businesses to the country. Additionally, President Obama mentions the plans to negotiate the Trans-Pacific Partnership and the Transatlantic Trade and Investment Partnership to boost exports, support American jobs, and promote trade with Asia, the Americas, and Europe. The proclamation encourages Americans to observe World Trade Week with events, trade shows, and educational programs to celebrate and inform about the benefits of trade to the nation and the global economy.